<header class="header">
  <h1>What Crops Grow in Short Growing Seasons?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    In short climates, heat accumulation matters more than calendar days.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, short growing seasons are defined by frost returning at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> sooner than in warmer regions.
    But the true limiting factor is often not just frost-free days — it’s total heat accumulation before first frost.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Defines a “Short” Growing Season?</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate frames frost timing using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost dates represent a typical-year planning boundary — not a guarantee.
  </p>

  <p>
    Many short-season climates have:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>90–120 frost-free days</li>
    <li>Limited accumulated Growing Degree Days (GDD)</li>
    <li>Cooler early and late season temperatures</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can determine your frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But season length alone doesn’t determine crop success.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Season = Limited Heat Budget</h2>

  <p>
    Crops develop based on accumulated heat — measured as Growing Degree Days (GDD).
    Most warm-season vegetables use a base temperature of 50°F.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler climates, daily GDD totals accumulate more slowly.
    Even if your frost-free window looks adequate on paper, heat accumulation may not be sufficient for long-season crops.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your typical seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For a deeper explanation of how frost and heat work together, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crops That Typically Fit Low-GDD Climates</h2>

  <p>
    While exact requirements vary by variety, short-season success usually means choosing crops that mature within lower GDD ranges.
  </p>

  <h3>Very Low Heat Requirement (Cool-Season Crops)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Lettuce</li>
    <li>Spinach</li>
    <li>Radishes</li>
    <li>Peas</li>
    <li>Kale</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These crops tolerate cooler temperatures and require minimal heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <h3>Moderate Heat Requirement</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Bush beans</li>
    <li>Zucchini</li>
    <li>Beets</li>
    <li>Carrots</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These crops generally mature within moderate GDD ranges and perform reliably in many short climates.
  </p>

  <h3>Higher Heat Requirement (Higher Risk in Short Seasons)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Large heirloom tomatoes</li>
    <li>Long-season corn</li>
    <li>Winter squash</li>
    <li>Peppers</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These crops often require higher accumulated GDD totals before first frost.
    In short climates, variety selection becomes critical.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Variety Selection Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Even within the same crop category, heat requirements can vary significantly.
  </p>

  <p>
    An early tomato variety may mature within 1,100–1,200 GDD.
    A large late-season beefsteak may require 1,600+.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your typical seasonal accumulation is 1,800 GDD, both may finish.
    If your accumulation is 1,400, the late variety carries higher maturity risk.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why “days to maturity” can be misleading in cold climates.
    (See: <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.)
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Extending Your Effective Season</h2>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, improving your margin often means:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Choosing earlier-maturing varieties</li>
    <li>Starting seeds indoors</li>
    <li>Taking advantage of warm microclimates</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If starting indoors meaningfully shifts transplant timing relative to frost risk,
    you can anchor your schedule using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, even earlier planting does not change total seasonal heat accumulation.
    It simply improves how much of that accumulation you can use.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Evaluate Crops for Your Climate</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Identify your 50% frost boundaries using the 32°F definition.</li>
    <li>Calculate your frost-free window length.</li>
    <li>Estimate total seasonal GDD accumulation.</li>
    <li>Select crops and varieties that fit comfortably within that heat budget.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Short growing seasons reward precision.
    The closer your crop’s heat requirement is to your seasonal total,
    the smaller your buffer becomes in a typical year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short growing seasons are constrained by frost timing and limited heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Frost dates use a 32°F threshold and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days measure how much development can occur before frost returns.</li>
    <li>Crop and variety selection should match your seasonal heat budget.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, maturity planning works best when frost timing and heat accumulation are evaluated together —
    not treated as separate factors.
  </p>
</section>